This paper deals with analyzing the relationships among parameters for quantifying the quality of research published in journals. The paper focuses on the impact factor, h-index, and g-index of a journal, which are commonly used in the field of computer science. The paper also discusses a generalized version of the impact factor, which is relevant to the sub-category of digital libraries (cs.DL). The analysis of relationships among these parameters is also relevant to information retrieval (cs.IR), cryptography (cs.CR), social networks (cs.SI), and databases (cs.DB).
